# Belgian Grand Prix (Spa-Francorchamps)

## Track Characteristics

Spa-Francorchamps is the longest circuit on the Formula 1 calendar and one of the most strategically complex.

* Circuit Length: 7.004 km
* Race Distance: 44 laps
* Corners: 19
* Surface Abrasiveness: Medium
* Tire Stress: High
* Brake Stress: Medium
* Elevation Change: Significant

The circuit combines:

* Long straights
* Fast corners
* Major elevation changes
* Variable weather zones

## Tire Behavior & Preferred Compounds

Common selections:

* C2, C3, C4
* Occasionally C1, C2, C3

Characteristics:

* Mixed tire demands.
* High loads through Eau Rouge/Raidillon and Pouhon.
* Balanced front and rear degradation.

## Typical Stint Lengths

Hard:

* 22-32 laps

Medium:

* 15-24 laps

Soft:

* 8-15 laps

## Common Strategy Patterns

### One-Stop

Historically common.

Examples:

* Medium → Hard
* Hard → Medium

### Two-Stop

Used when:

* Tire degradation increases.
* Safety Cars intervene.
* Weather changes occur.

### Reactive Strategies

Spa rewards adaptability more than most circuits.

## Weather Tendencies

Among the most unpredictable races in Formula 1.

Typical conditions:

* Rain in one sector only.
* Dry and wet portions simultaneously.
* Rapid weather changes.

Weather conditions can differ dramatically around the circuit.

## Safety Car & VSC Probability

Safety Car probability: High

Reasons:

* Long lap.
* High-speed corners.
* Variable weather.
* Historic accident zones.

## Undercut vs Overcut Analysis

### Undercut

Strong due to long lap time and fresh tire advantage.

### Overcut

Can also be effective because:

* Tire degradation is manageable.
* Traffic often dictates outcomes.

Overall:

* Undercut effectiveness: High
* Overcut effectiveness: Medium-High

## Overtaking Opportunities

Major zones:

* Les Combes
* Kemmel Straight
* Bus Stop Chicane

Spa is one of the best overtaking circuits on the calendar.

## Qualifying Importance

Moderate.

Race pace and strategy frequently outweigh starting position.

## Strategic Notes

* Weather forecasting is critical.
* Teams frequently prepare multiple strategy trees before the race.
* Safety Cars often create major strategic swings.
* Tire selection before changing weather conditions can determine outcomes.

## Historical Strategy Trends (2018-Present)

* One-stop races have often been successful.
* Mixed-weather races have rewarded flexible decision-making.
* Safety Cars and changing conditions routinely alter optimal strategies.
* Teams frequently prioritize adaptability over strict pre-race planning.

